uclear energy-producing countries face not only technical problems but also social and ethical issues. Nuclear Waste Management in Canada provides a critical counterpoint to the favourable position taken by government and industry. The contributors build their case by exploring the following key issues and developments: What do frequently used terms such as safety, risk, and acceptability really mean? How and why did the public consultation process in Canada fail to address ethical and social issues? What is the significance and potential of a public consultation process that involves diverse interests, epistemologies, and actors, including Aboriginal peoples? And how do we ensure that the frameworks for discussion are inclusive and ethical? This collection is a timely antidote to the uncertainty, ambiguity, and ignorance that surrounds discussions about nuclear energy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aTechnology & Engineering / Environmental / Waste Management.2bisacsh1 aDurant, Darrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurant, Darrin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFuji Johnson, Genevieve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Genevieve Fuji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Brenda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimmerman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010